Here is an example in C#:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;

class Program
{
    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        Dictionary<string, int[]> oldDict = new Dictionary<string, int[]>();
        // Add entries to oldDict

        Dictionary<string, int[]> newDict = new Dictionary<string, int[]>(oldDict.Count);
        HashSet<int> valuesSoFar = new HashSet<int>();

        foreach (var kvp in oldDict)
        {
            bool hasDup = false;
            foreach (var val in kvp.Value)
            {
                if (valuesSoFar.Contains(val))
                {
                    hasDup = true;
                    break;
                }
            }
            if (!hasDup)
            {
                newDict.Add(kvp.Key, kvp.Value);
                foreach (var val in kvp.Value)
                {
                    valuesSoFar.Add(val);
                }
            }
        }

        // Use newDict
    }
}
```

In this example, `oldDict` is the original dictionary with the potential duplicates. We create a new dictionary called `newDict`, which will contain only the entries that are not duplicates. 

We also create a `HashSet` called `valuesSoFar`, which will keep track of all the values seen so far in the process of iterating through the old dictionary.

We then iterate through `oldDict` and check if the current key/value pair has a duplicate value in `valuesSoFar`. If it doesn't, we add the key/value pair to `newDict`, and also add all the values from the value array to the `valuesSoFar` hash set for future checking.

At the end, `newDict` contains only the non-duplicate entries.

Apologies for the confusion earlier. Here's how you can remove dictionary entries where the value is contained in another entry:

```csharp
static void Main(string[] args)
{
    // Your original dictionary
    Dictionary<string, int[]> dict = new Dictionary<string, int[]>
    {
        { "A", new[] { 1, 2 } },
        { "B", new[] { 2, 3 } },
        { "C", new[] { 4, 5 } },
        { "D", new[] { 1, 2, 3 } }
    };

    // New dictionary to store filtered entries
    Dictionary<string, int[]> filteredDict = new Dictionary<string, int[]>();

    // Iterate through each key-value pair in the original dictionary
    foreach (var kvp in dict)
    {
        // Flag to track if current value is contained in another value of the dictionary
        bool isDuplicate = false;

        // Iterate through the other key-value pairs in dictionary
        foreach (var otherKvp in dict)
        {
            // If current key is same as other key, skip
            if (kvp.Key == otherKvp.Key) continue;

            // Check if all values in current value array are present in the other value array
            if (kvp.Value.All(otherKvp.Value.Contains))
            {
                isDuplicate = true;
                break;
            }
        }

        // If current value is not contained in any other value array, add it to filtered dictionary
        if (!isDuplicate) filteredDict.Add(kvp.Key, kvp.Value);
    }

    // Output filtered dictionary
    foreach (var kvp in filteredDict)
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"{kvp.Key} - {string.Join(",", kvp.Value)}");
    }
}
```

This code produces the following output:

```
C - 4,5
D - 1,2,3
```

Here, you can see that only entries with unique values are included in the `filteredDict`. The `isDuplicate` flag is used to check whether the current value is contained in any other value of the dictionary. If it is contained, it is not added to the `filteredDict`.

