Here's an example of how to use aggregation in MongoDB with C# to retrieve data for a list of names:

```csharp
using MongoDB.Bson;
using MongoDB.Driver;

// Get the MongoDB database and collection objects
string connectionString = "mongodb://localhost:27017";
string databaseName = "myDatabase";
string collectionName = "myCollection";
IMongoClient client = new MongoClient(connectionString);
IMongoDatabase database = client.GetDatabase(databaseName);
IMongoCollection<BsonDocument> collection = database.GetCollection<BsonDocument>(collectionName);

// List of names we want to retrieve data for
List<string> names = new List<string> { "John", "Jane", "Bob" };

// Build the aggregation pipeline
var pipeline = new BsonDocument[]
{
    new BsonDocument("$match", new BsonDocument("name", new BsonDocument("$in", new BsonArray(names)))),
    new BsonDocument("$group", new BsonDocument("_id", "$name").Add("count", new BsonDocument("$sum", 1)))
};

// Execute the aggregation pipeline and retrieve the results
var results = collection.Aggregate<BsonDocument>(pipeline).ToList();

foreach (var result in results)
{
    string name = result.GetValue("_id").AsString;
    int count = result.GetValue("count").AsInt32;

    Console.WriteLine($"{name}: {count}");
}
```

In this example, we have a MongoDB collection with documents that contain a `name` field. We want to retrieve data for a list of names, and count the number of documents that match each name.

We first connect to the MongoDB database and collection using the `MongoClient`, `MongoDatabase`, and `MongoCollection` classes.

We then create a list of names that we want to retrieve data for.

Next, we build the aggregation pipeline using BSON documents. The pipeline has two stages: `$match` and `$group`. The `$match` stage filters the documents by the names in the `names` list using the `$in` operator. The `$group` stage groups the documents by the `name` field, and counts the number of documents using the `$sum` operator.

Finally, we execute the aggregation pipeline using the `Aggregate` method of the collection object, and retrieve the results as a list of `BsonDocument` objects. We then iterate through the results and print out the name and count for each result.

Note that in this example, we're assuming that the `name` field is a string. If it's another data type, you'll need to adjust the code accordingly.

You can modify the `$match` stage of the aggregation pipeline to match on the first and last names separately, and then use the `$group` stage to group by the combined full name. Here's how you can modify the code to do this:

```csharp
using MongoDB.Bson;
using MongoDB.Driver;

// Get the MongoDB database and collection objects
string connectionString = "mongodb://localhost:27017";
string databaseName = "myDatabase";
string collectionName = "myCollection";
IMongoClient client = new MongoClient(connectionString);
IMongoDatabase database = client.GetDatabase(databaseName);
IMongoCollection<BsonDocument> collection = database.GetCollection<BsonDocument>(collectionName);

// List of names (first and last name for each item)
List<string[]> names = new List<string[]>
{
    new string[] { "John", "Doe" },
    new string[] { "Jane", "Smith" },
    new string[] { "Bob", "Johnson" }
};

// Build the aggregation pipeline
var pipeline = new BsonDocument[]
{
    new BsonDocument("$match", new BsonDocument
        {
            { "firstName", new BsonDocument("$in", new BsonArray(names.Select(n => n[0]))) },
            { "lastName", new BsonDocument("$in", new BsonArray(names.Select(n => n[1]))) }
        }),
    new BsonDocument("$group", new BsonDocument("_id", new BsonDocument
        {
            { "firstName", "$firstName" },
            { "lastName", "$lastName" }
        }).Add("count", new BsonDocument("$sum", 1)))
};

// Execute the aggregation pipeline and retrieve the results
var results = collection.Aggregate<BsonDocument>(pipeline).ToList();

foreach (var result in results)
{
    string firstName = result.GetValue("_id.firstName").AsString;
    string lastName = result.GetValue("_id.lastName").AsString;
    int count = result.GetValue("count").AsInt32;

    Console.WriteLine($"{firstName} {lastName}: {count}");
}
```

In this example, the `names` list contains an array of strings for each name, with the first and last name as separate elements.

We modify the `$match` stage of the pipeline to match on the `firstName` field with the first elements of each name array in the `names` list, and on the `lastName` field with the second elements of each name array.

We then modify the `$group` stage of the pipeline to group by a combined full name field, which is an object with `firstName` and `lastName` fields taken from the document fields. We then count the number of documents using the `$sum` operator.

Finally, we retrieve the results, iterate through them, and print out the full name and count for each result.
